




TY  - JOUR
T1  - An Economic Basis for the "National Defense Argument" for Aiding Certain Industries
AU  - Thompson, Earl A.
Y1  - 1979/02/01
PY  - 1979
DA  - 1979/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260737
DO  - 10.1086/260737
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1
EP  - 36
VL  - 87
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Two alternative theories, each generating a "national defense argument" for protectionism, are developed and tested. The theory surviving the tests states that wartime price controls imply an undervaluation of peacetime stocks of capital which produce the war-controlled outputs. Optimal policy responses to these undervaluations are derived. For example: Nonimported, undervalued capital goods should receive domestic subsidies; undervalued capital goods, imported in peacetime but not in wartime, should receive import protection; and undervalued capital goods which are imported in wartime should be granted cartel status. An application to the United States indicates that the theoretical optimum is approximated by observed policy.
AB  - Two alternative theories, each generating a "national defense argument" for protectionism, are developed and tested. The theory surviving the tests states that wartime price controls imply an undervaluation of peacetime stocks of capital which produce the war-controlled outputs. Optimal policy responses to these undervaluations are derived. For example: Nonimported, undervalued capital goods should receive domestic subsidies; undervalued capital goods, imported in peacetime but not in wartime, should receive import protection; and undervalued capital goods which are imported in wartime should be granted cartel status. An application to the United States indicates that the theoretical optimum is approximated by observed policy.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260737
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260737
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Possibility of Rational Social Choice in an Economy
AU  - Bailey, Martin J.
Y1  - 1979/02/01
PY  - 1979
DA  - 1979/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260738
DO  - 10.1086/260738
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 37
EP  - 56
VL  - 87
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper examines the implications of an error or oversight in the statement and proof of Arrow's celebrated General Possibility Theorem. Besides showing that, strictly speaking, the theorem is false, we show that the force of the correctly stated theorem and of most of its descendants applies only to a class of election procedures and not to social choice in an economy. A Bergson welfare function can be constructed that satisfies all the stated Arrow axioms and conditions, although the construction is unnecessary for consistent, effective social choice.
AB  - This paper examines the implications of an error or oversight in the statement and proof of Arrow's celebrated General Possibility Theorem. Besides showing that, strictly speaking, the theorem is false, we show that the force of the correctly stated theorem and of most of its descendants applies only to a class of election procedures and not to social choice in an economy. A Bergson welfare function can be constructed that satisfies all the stated Arrow axioms and conditions, although the construction is unnecessary for consistent, effective social choice.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260738
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260738
Y2  - 2024/03/22
